A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the Mediterranean migration crisis.
First, the international community and Europe apply a system cruelly ill-suited to protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of this system's ineffectiveness, populist actors ceaselessly exploit fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies that have taken some 70 years of relentless efforts to build.
It is for this reason that it is essential that a truly proactive approach be undertaken this year at both the European and global levels.
In September next, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a robust global system for protecting the most disadvantaged migrants and refugees.
Let's engage in a meaningful and lasting way.
This necessary commitment was cruelly lacking throughout the year 2015.
In fact, the international community would have been able to limit the gravity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no less than four million refugees.
With only approximately 10 billion euros, these countries would have been more capable of housing, feeding, and providing education to the refugees, thereby reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany up to 21 billion euros every year in the years to come.
The financial implications of the crisis are in no way comparable to its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, only to endure an exhausting journey through the Balkans.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, with many European countries turning their backs on the survivors by refusing them asylum.
The most cynical politicians have ruthlessly exploited the fears of citizens, promoting a loathsome nationalist vision, either by ignoring or distorting the migrants' life experience.
In the United States, for instance, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has committed a terrorist act.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they benefit from social benefits.
Yet, extremist parties are flirting dangerously with the prospect of taking power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support even within long-standing liberal strongholds.
Extremist anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success is also leading traditional parties to promote their own anti-immigration policies.
This situation has seriously undermined European cooperation.
The EU's program to address the million refugees who arrived on its shores has only managed to "relocate" 190.
Controls at the borders of at least six Schengen countries have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today as nationalist and incompetent.
The resolution of this crisis is not limited to Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
Whatever the case, the EU is undoubtedly facing a threat to its own existence today, which it can only overcome by firmly demonstrating the international solidarity and leadership it is capable of.
It is up to the member states to take the initiative in proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority lies in establishing safe and legal channels for refugees to reach Europe.
It's not a question of saying that every migrant in distress must be welcomed.
It is up to the EU to be systematically more generous in determining the number of refugees to admit, and to employ orderly mechanisms to facilitate their entry.
Such a system would allow for the protection of migrants while safeguarding Europe (thanks to the possibility of fully examining the requests).
Beyond a strategy aimed at discouraging asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would allow Europe to project an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
This approach would also encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a robust global system for protecting vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This objective will above all require more countries to agree to accept refugees.
Over the past few years, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has only managed to resettle fewer than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Several million of them end up in a prolonged migration situation, with an estimated average duration of 25 years, trapped in a kind of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a potential return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to agree to accept a cumulative total of nearly one million refugees each year, either through resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other type of visa.
Canada having announced that it will accept 50,000 Syrian refugees on its own this year, this is clearly an achievable objective.
In the same timeframe, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current state of affairs, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually required for each refugee for housing, food, healthcare, education, and vocational training in the first years of resettlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for instance, water supply systems are strained by the massive influx of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European and other countries rid themselves of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these individuals continue to be viewed as a burden, or even a threat to security, reactionary political forces will only gain ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
In contrast, if host countries succeed in integrating migrants with enthusiasm, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through increased revenue).
Last month in Paris, the international community demonstrated its ability to subordinate its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, it is necessary that a similar effort aims to build a better system for protecting migrants.
It's a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of civic health for democratic societies around the world.
